&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;  output &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; relevant_text&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;last&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;gsub&lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0a3069&#34;&gt;/ethd/&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0a3069&#34;&gt;&amp;#34;eth0&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;  &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;File&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;open&lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;config_file&lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;,&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0a3069&#34;&gt;&amp;#34;w&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;){&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;|&lt;/span&gt;file&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;|&lt;/span&gt; file&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;puts output &lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;  &lt;span style=&#34;color:#6639ba&#34;&gt;system&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;(&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0a3069&#34;&gt;&amp;#34;reboot&amp;#34;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;)&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#cf222e&#34;&gt;end&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://jerodsanto.net/src/ruby/vm_mac_fixer.rb&#34;&gt;Download&lt;/a&gt; and use it if you‚Äôd like.&lt;/p&gt;

      &lt;p&gt;Here‚Äôs a quickie. You just compiled &lt;a href=&#34;http://asterisk.org/&#34;&gt;Asterisk&lt;/a&gt; on your &lt;a href=&#34;http://debian.org/&#34;&gt;Debian&lt;/a&gt; server and you want to make sure it starts when you reboot. Here‚Äôs how:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Look in the &lt;code&gt;/contrib/init.d&lt;/code&gt; folder of your Asterisk source directory. You‚Äôll see a file called &lt;code&gt;rc.debian.asterisk&lt;/code&gt;. If you installed Asterisk to the default location, don‚Äôt worry about editing this file. If you installed to a different location (eg - /usr/local), change the following line in the file:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#fff;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#953800&#34;&gt;DAEMON&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt;/usr/sbin/asterisk
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Point this at your Asterisk binary. Not sure where it is? Just type &lt;code&gt;which asterisk&lt;/code&gt; from the command line and it will show you the full path.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Next, copy the file into the &lt;code&gt;/etc/init.d/&lt;/code&gt; directory like so:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#fff;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;cp rc.debian.asterisk /etc/init.d/asterisk
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;(NOTE: I am renaming the file on purpose)&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now you can control Asterisk by executing this script. Make sure it starts and stops before continuing:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#fff;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;/etc/init.d/asterisk start
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;Starting Asterisk PBX: asterisk.
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;/etc/init.d/asterisk stop
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;Stopping Asterisk PBX: asterisk.
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Finally, make the system run this script during the boot process:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#fff;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;update-rc.d asterisk defaults
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Done and done. Reboot and check the process list just to be sure!&lt;/p&gt;

      &lt;p&gt;I began hacking on Asterisk using the &lt;a href=&#34;http://adhearsion.com/&#34;&gt;Adhearsion&lt;/a&gt; framework a few weeks ago. Despite initial setbacks, I am now having an absolute blast.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;I put together a little &lt;a href=&#34;http://macromates.com/&#34;&gt;TextMate&lt;/a&gt; bundle to aide in my development and figured I‚Äôd share it out as a starting point for others. I am not a TextMate or Adhearsion pro (yet) so I am sure there are a ton of improvements to be made.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;/uploads/2008/08/adhearsion-tmbundle.png&#34;&gt;&lt;img class=&#34;aligncenter size-full wp-image-81&#34; title=&#34;adhearsion-tmbundle&#34; src=&#34;/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/adhearsion-tmbundle.png&#34; height=&#34;131&#34; alt=&#34;adhearsion-tmbundle&#34; width=&#34;495&#34; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;So, please fork my &lt;a href=&#34;http://github.com/jerodsanto/adhearsion-tmbundle/tree/master&#34;&gt;GitHub repo&lt;/a&gt; and make improvements. We will all benefit from them!&lt;/p&gt;

      &lt;p&gt;Ok, this bugs the crap out of me. I set up a shiny new Debian 4.0 base install and go on my merry way, meanwhile the system time is off by a long shot! I only notice when it starts to hurt‚Ä¶&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Here‚Äôs how to synchronize your Debian system‚Äôs time with network time servers, in a few simple steps (use sudo as needed):&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Install the necessary packages:&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#fff;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;apt-get install ntp ntpdate
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ol start=&#34;2&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Stop the NTP daemon for now (apt-get will start the service upon successful installation):&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#fff;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;/etc/init.d/ntp stop
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ol start=&#34;3&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Manually synchronize the system clock to the NTP server pool:&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#fff;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;ntpdate pool.ntp.org
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;3.5) An explanation: the NTP server daemon will fail to sync with the NTP servers if the system time is too far from the NTP servers time so its best to manually synchronize once to get your system time close enough.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;ol start=&#34;4&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;Restart the NTP daemon:&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#fff;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;/etc/init.d/ntp start
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;ol start=&#34;5&#34;&gt;
&lt;li&gt;(Optionally) Verify that the NTP daemon is synchronized by checking the syslog:&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ol&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#fff;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;grep ntpd /var/log/syslog &lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;|&lt;/span&gt; tail
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;ntpd&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;6348&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;: synchronized to 74.53.198.146, stratum &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;2&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;ntpd&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;6348&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;: kernel &lt;span style=&#34;color:#6639ba&#34;&gt;time&lt;/span&gt; sync enabled &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;0001&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;ntpd&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;[&lt;/span&gt;6348&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;]&lt;/span&gt;: synchronized to 128.10.19.24, stratum &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;1&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;Your output may vary, but it should look similar to mine.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;That‚Äôs all for now!&lt;/p&gt;

      &lt;p&gt;Sometimes Rails just blows me away, and it just happened a few moments ago. When it comes to dealing with dates and their formats between different databases, Ruby, time zones, etc, etc‚Ä¶it can get pretty nasty. I can‚Äôt believe the amount of help Rails delivers in this arena.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Let‚Äôs assume I‚Äôm trying to track phone calls across time ranges; daily, monthly, yearly. This can usually become troublesome as I‚Äôll have to query the database to find only records inside those ranges. I will spare you all the lame ways I tried to implement this by hand and just show you the code of how to create a named scope and call it using Rails 2.1.0.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#fff;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-ruby&#34; data-lang=&#34;ruby&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#57606a&#34;&gt;# in call.rb&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#cf222e&#34;&gt;class&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;Call&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;&amp;lt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;ActiveRecord&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;::&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;Base&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;  named_scope &lt;span style=&#34;color:#032f62&#34;&gt;:by_month&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;,&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#6639ba&#34;&gt;lambda&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;{&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;|&lt;/span&gt;d&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;|&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;{&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#032f62&#34;&gt;:conditions&lt;/span&gt;  &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;=&amp;gt;&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;{&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#032f62&#34;&gt;:date&lt;/span&gt;  &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;=&amp;gt;&lt;/span&gt; d&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;beginning_of_month&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;..&lt;/span&gt;d&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;end_of_month &lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;}&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;}&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#1f2328&#34;&gt;}&lt;/span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;What this does is create a new scope called &lt;code&gt;by_month&lt;/code&gt; that lets me query the database‚Ä¶by month :) and pass in a Date object as a single parameter. Rails/ActiveRecord will take the Date object and pass it to the lambda block, which calls the two Rails helpers ( &lt;code&gt;beginning_of_month&lt;/code&gt; and &lt;code&gt;end_of_month&lt;/code&gt; ) to find the date range for the month my Date object is in. It then queries the database using that date range!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Awesome.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now I can access the records I want like this:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#fff;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-ruby&#34; data-lang=&#34;ruby&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;this_months_calls &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;=&lt;/span&gt; &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;Call&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;by_month &lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;Date&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;color:#0550ae&#34;&gt;.&lt;/span&gt;today
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/code&gt;&lt;/pre&gt;&lt;/div&gt;&lt;p&gt;And Rails will return all the calls that were recorded during the current month. Love it.&lt;/p&gt;

      &lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://liltompeep.heroku.com/&#34;&gt;lil tom peep&lt;/a&gt; is a new web application I wrote to fix a problem I had with web surfing. I hate having to manually check up on semi-static web pages like blog comment streams and firmware update pages (basically anything missing RSS).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;Now I just submit the page url and my email address to &lt;a href=&#34;http://liltompeep.heroku.com/&#34;&gt;lil tom peep&lt;/a&gt; and he does the checking for me. Pretty basic, but very useful to me.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/ltp.png&#34;&gt;&lt;img class=&#34;aligncenter size-full wp-image-83&#34; title=&#34;ltp&#34; src=&#34;/wp-content/uploads/2008/08/ltp.png&#34; height=&#34;116&#34; alt=&#34;ltp&#34; width=&#34;406&#34; /&gt;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&#34;http://liltompeep.heroku.com/&#34;&gt;ltp&lt;/a&gt; is powered by &lt;a href=&#34;http://sinatrarb.com/&#34;&gt;Sinatra&lt;/a&gt;. Check out the &lt;a href=&#34;http://liltompeep.com/props&#34;&gt;props&lt;/a&gt; page to see all the technologies involved. Possible future features include RSS-integration and a bookmarklet. Let me know if you have any feature requests or encounter any bugs while using the service. Enjoy!&lt;/p&gt;

      &lt;p&gt;In case you muck up your &lt;code&gt;/etc/apt/sources.list&lt;/code&gt; and want to set it back to the defaults, just copy and paste this in:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class=&#34;highlight&#34;&gt;&lt;pre tabindex=&#34;0&#34; style=&#34;background-color:#fff;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;&#34;&gt;&lt;code class=&#34;language-bash&#34; data-lang=&#34;bash&#34;&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;deb http://ftp.debian.org/debian/ etch main
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;deb-src http://ftp.debian.org/debian/ etch main
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;
&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/span&gt;&lt;span style=&#34;display:flex;&#34;&gt;&lt;span&gt;deb http://security.debian.org/ etch/updates main contrib
